etween what they learn from a book and what s really out there  That connection extends even further as Timmons procures grants for materials for real research culminating in published articles with cadets among the authors   If I can get a student interested in a problem  then they re willing to sort out the difficulties  said Timmons  The chemistry lab at VMI offers a chance for cadets to couple their creativity with the discipline of Institute life  There  Timmons said   We build some beautiful molecules   If I can get a student interested in a problem  then they re willing to sort out the difficulties  Col  Daren Timmons Professor and Department Head  Chemistry John C  Allen  62 Institute Professorship in Chemistry Ph D  Texas A M University Specialty  Inorganic chemistry   Share this entry Share on Facebook Share on Twitter Share on Google  Share on Linkedin Share on Tumblr Share on Reddit Share by Mail Cool Chemistry May 1  2014 in Academic  Faculty and Staff  Stories  by Kate That s the message VMI cadets start with in Col  Daren Timmons  rat chemistry class  They get it as soon as the professor of chemistry  who holds a doctorate from Texas A M University  gets out the luminescent material that is the focus of much of his research with cadets  Shine an ultraviolet light   that is  a black light   on it  and it glows  And so do the faces of a certain number of cadets in every one of these classes  Many are prompted to ask   What s going on here  That s the kind of question Timmons likes the stimulate and the kind that can launch a four year quest to build rigid and fluid networks at the molecular level that can be applied in products as wide ranging as LCDs and pharmaceuticals  After all  chemistry at VMI  chemistry in Timmons  classroom and lab  is about students creating  new science   At VMI we get the students involved in answering real questions  said Timmons  That process means connecting the classroom with the lab  Teaching and learning in Timmons  cla